body:
> Don’t you just have to remove the default value for the DTO to achieve this?

@xabbuh Removing default value for DTO results in expected status code however, there is no feedback for client what went wrong.

> The validation is meant to be run on a paylod fetched from the request. Basically, you run the validation on user input.

@derrabus empty input is still an input therefore validation may be required to run. 

> apps might rely on the current behavior, so enabling the validation for everyone might break code downstream

From Symfony 6.4 upwards, sending empty input to following code

```php
final class ApiDTO
{
    public string $foo = '';
}

class FooController extends AbstractController
{
    #[Route("/foo", methods: ["GET"])]
    public function __invoke(#[MapQueryString(validationFailedStatusCode: 400)] ApiDTO $dto): JsonResponse {
        dd($dto);
    }
}
```
client gets `400` without feedback about what went wrong. The same happens when empty input is sent and DTO has assertions.

Setting default value for controller parameter makes `$dto` to be a new instance of `ApiDTO`. Without any assertions this is expected behavior. The only thing that may change is when DTO has assertions. However, with default instance of DTO being invalid which can be declared with 

```php
final class ApiDTO
{
    #[Assert\NotBlank]
    public string $foo = '';
}
```

controller gets called with invalid parameter due no validation was executed. This require to run validation directly in controller which, in case of sending proper input, ends up executing the same validation on the same object twice which makes this feature redundant.

I can imagine people decide to use common `Form` instead of mapping for that case because it is simply not supported.

>If we look at it a a similarity to Form component, default value validation is a fact possible with data_class option which is default instance of DTO mapped from request payload and used for validation. With empty request, simply new instance is used.

It's a good point. We don't need a default value to achieve the same result here. We can instantiate the object from the `$argument->getType()`. Well wait, that's what the serializer is currently doing with `$this->serializer->denormalize($data, $argument->getType())`.

Therefore, let the empty array `$data` continue if there is no default value set:
```php
private function mapQueryString(Request $request, ArgumentMetadata $argument, MapQueryString $attribute): ?object
{
    if (!($data = $request->query->all()) && $argument->hasDefaultValue()) { // <-- line changed
        return null;
    }

    return $this->serializer->denormalize($data, $argument->getType(), null, $attribute->serializationContext + self::CONTEXT_DENORMALIZE + ['filter_bool' => true]);
}
```
That's it! Denormalizing with `data = []` will initialize the object anyway, and the validation will provide a clear error message. There is no BC break, as we are currently getting an error under the same scenario but without a message.
